Description.val:
Underwater Explosive Ordnance Disposal (EOD) program supplies EOD and Maritime Expeditionary forces with the necessary allowance outfitting, and diving and diving-related equipment aligned to fulfill assigned missions that includes Expeditionary Mine Countermeasures (ExMCM), other Maritime Expeditionary missions, and Marine Mammal Systems (MMS) operations. Most equipment must have inherently low acoustic and magnetic signatures to support maritime operations in the vicinity of influence fired ordnance.  This funding supports outfitting the Navy's only comprehensive capability in the fleet that can conduct full spectrum detect-to-engage expeditionary MCM missions. Specifically, the Underwater Explosive Ordnance Disposal (EOD) program supports EOD Groups, Units, and Detachments worldwide as well as Mobile Driving and Salvage Units (MDSUs) across the globe.

The establishment of ExMCM Forces under the direction of Commander, US Fleet Forces Command has resulted in an increased inventory requirement for Underwater EOD systems and equipment, with a resultant requirement for re-aligned procurement and fielding priorities. The nature of the missions assigned to EOD and MCM forces under OPNAVINST 3501.97H, Required Operational Capabilities & Projected Operational Environments (ROC/POE), require an aggregated set of systems and equipment to perform the wide range of mine countermeasures, underwater detection, location, investigation, force protection, and neutralization tasks that comprise the mission set. The requirements for the procurement of each of these system suites are articulated in OPNAV approved requirements documents in accordance with DoD Directive 5000.2, SECNAVINST 5000.2E, and the JCIDS process as defined by CJSCINST 3170.01 and defined by the JROC approved ExMCM ICD.

Naval Special Warfare (NSW) - FY 2019 continues procurement of a service-common systems program for Naval Special Warfare's (NSW) Unmanned Undersea Vehicles (UUVs). Naval Special Warfare currently employs UUVs as an intelligence collection platform, building situational awareness of the Undersea Domain, and prior to conducting clandestine operations in support of the highest strategic objectives. UUVs are critical to NSW's undersea component, mission planning for anti-access and area denial (A2AD) environments, and the current fight against violent extremist organizations.  The use of open architecture, untethered platforms not only buys down risk to mission and force, but also provides the operational commander a diversified menu of employment options.

Justification.val:
FY 2019 funding is required to continue procurement and fielding of Underwater EOD program systems and equipment to outfit Expeditionary MCM Companies, EOD and Mobile Salvage units with advanced sensors and hardware required to accomplish their OPNAV approved Required Operational Capability and Projected Operational Environments. This equipment will allow warfighters to detect, locate, investigate, neutralize and render safe unexploded ordnance including improvised explosive devices. The increase in FY2019 supports the Expeditionary MCM companies to support their increase in deployments and Table of Allowance requirements including the MK18 Mod 1 unmanned undersea vehicle (UUV). 

Additionally, FY2019 funding is required to procure product improvements needed for systems designed and first produced over 40 years ago, as well as the production engineering and integrated logistics support needed for all Expeditionary MCM Companies, EOD Units, and Expeditionary Salvage units. These systems provide the only expeditionary mine interdiction capability in the US Navy.  If these forces are not properly outfitted lives may be lost, access to sea lanes of communication could be severed, and risk to transiting forces will be elevated.   Specifically, upgrade kits to MK 18 Family of Systems will be procured to provide increased MCM capability through procurement of the Mod 1 Block C upgrade kits; MOTS ROV enhancements will be procured to provide EOD Response capabilities for mine/unexploded ordinance (UXO) target prosecution; improved diver sensor tools will be procured to provide enhanced target detection and localization capabilities; and auxiliary equipment procured that is required to fully outfit systems to perform their intended missions.

OCO: 
Naval Special Warfare (NSW) - FY 2019 will support the replacement of the Mk 18 Mod 1 unmanned undersea vehicle variant that US Navy SEALs currently employ as an intelligence collection platform  prior to conducting clandestine operations in support of Operation Inherent Resolve and other missions. Unmanned Undersea Vehicles (UUVs) enable NSW to extend its range of operations from manned undersea vehicles and enable access in diverse and hazardous areas. The MK18 MOD1 SWORDFISH UUV is an unmanned tool that increases the range of NSW influence and reduces risk to US Navy SEALs through increased battle space awareness in maritime environments. Forward deployed NSW personnel are using UUVs in contingency and high-threat environments in operations against violent extremist organizations.

Underwater EOD Programs - FY19 OCO funding will provide resources to procure needed Expeditionary Mine Countermeasures (ExMCM) equipment including Underwater Breathing Apparatus (UBAs), Diver held tools, and other associated equipment needed to outfit ExMCM Companies.

Name.@footnote: CE 1.1.1 MIW-VIP: FY2019 efforts will focus on ranging RHIBS and unmanned systems to determine specific signature characteristics that will aid in development of tactics and procedures to ensure survivability of these systems in various operation conditions. MIW-VIP measures magnetic and acoustic signatures using existing ranges and portable ranges (Forward Area Combined Degaussing and Acoustic Range (FACDAR)).  Measurements are taken in both home port areas and deployment areas to assess susceptibility to various threat mines. Efforts across the FYDP include ranging RHIBS, newly acquired equipment (related OPNAV approved Table of Allowance items) and unmanned systems (i.e. MK 18 Mod's 1 & 2).

CE 2.1.10 AUXILLIARY EQUIPMENT (MK 18 Family of Systems): Provides for procurement of OPNAV approved fleet outfitting of equipment other than UUVs that is required for the MK 18 and MK 19 systems to accomplish their missions. This includes equipment required for deployment, pre-mission planning and post mission analysis of the data collected by the UUVs. In addition, new procurement auxiliary kits will be procured to support enhancements to legacy fleet systems through engineering changes, system upgrades and obsolescence of legacy auxiliary kits.

CE 2.1.11 MK 19 FoS ROV Upgrades: Previously HULS Retrofit Kits - MK 19 FoS upgrades leverage advancements in robotic manipulators, target recognition software, user interface, and explosive recognition and neutralization that have been achieved in land robots and which can now be integrated into undersea remotely operated vehicles. These upgrades to previously fielded EOD response ROVs will enable more rapid reacquisition, identification and neutralization of mine like targets found by the MK 18 or other MCM search assets.

Name.@footnote: CE 2.1.12 MODIFIED OFF-THE-SHELF (MOTS) REMOTELY OPERATED VEHICLE (ROV): Provides for procurement funding for OPNAV approved fleet outfitting of a modified-off-the-shelf Remotely Operated Vehicle. This capability will significantly reduce operational risk to divers when investigation and interdiction of a underwater is required, i.e. sea mine or underwater Improved Explosive Device.

CE 2.1.13 UW DIVER INTEGRATION SENSORS: Provides for the procurement of a family of systems based on Modified-Off-The Shelf (MTS), mature technologies and upgrades to Diver Integrated Sensors. Unit cost of individual retrofit kits may vary based on number and type of technology included in the kit.
CE 2.1.15 INFLUENCE SIGNATURE REDUCTION: Funding procures reduction of acoustic, magnetic and seismic signatures for equipment used in a suspected minefield.

Remarks.val: [Hardware/Recurring] CE 1.1) Ex MCM Outfitting: This funding resources the procurement of Expeditionary UUV-based systems and support equipment on the OPNAV approved Table of Allowance.  Procurement of this equipment will allow the UUV-based systems to be deployed globally and employed from a wide variety of shipboard platforms at sea as well as small craft.  ExMCM cost elements include MK 18 MOD 1 and Mod 2 UUVs which provides for procurement of UUV MK 18 vehicles, which will be employed in operational missions in Shallow Water (SW) and Very Shallow Water (VSW) environments including rotational deployments to the Fifth Fleet, Sixth Fleet, and Seventh Fleet areas of responsibility .Additional  ExMCM procurement cost elements include Open Water Transport Systems (OWTS), Shipboard Charging Containers (SCC), Auxiliary Equipment sets, Mission support Equipment, Maintenance Kits, and  Fleet Support Kits.   The various kits comprise the ancillary and support equipment necessary to outfit an  ExMCM Company with a complete set of Mk 18 UUV related equipment and are procured from a variety of OEMs and sources.
